,Recommended,313340,33360772,Posted: 7 July,all,¤The Flying Knife¤,"Let's get it clear, first of all: THIS IS NOT A GAME. Anyone who reviews Mountain as if it is your traditional game needs to reevaluate it under a different perspective.Mountain can be seen as a screensaver, visual entertainment, aesthetically appealing content--anything along these categories. If all you do from morning to night is play mainstream high-action games (i.e. Dota 2, CS:GO, etc.), you probably will not immediately be able to enjoy the abstract simplicity that this game offers.Let's get down straight to the meat of this. The only user interaction that you have at your disposal is using your mouse to move the mountain three-dimensionally, your keyboard to play music notes (which can be used to unlock easter eggs), picking up and organising ""artefacts"" that drop on your mountain overtime, and the almighty eye of the beholder to watch the mountain collect random objects and pile up on the mountain. The biggest input the player has to the game is three questions asked in the beginning, prompting the user to draw three images to represent three different things (i.e. mother).The only spontaneous events to occur are a meteor that may destroy your mountain and changing weathers/seasons. Ocasionally your mountain will ""think"" and provide some interesting, philosophical annotations about its existence. If you leave the game open for a few minutes, your camera eventually will zoom out into an outer-space view of the mountain.I would recommend it buying it especially for how cheap it is (kudos to the developers for not overrating their game). I really just leave the game open and use it to take a break from my studying to look up at the screen and just relax a bit.You can check out why Mountain is a legitimate thing here:http://www.pcgamer.com/why-the-media-loves-mountain-but-steam-users-are-calling-it-a-screensaver/"
