,Not Recommended,313340,31461982,Posted: 30 April,all,Liberteer,"Being swallowed by the Everything's hype wave (actually, there's no hype, it was just me realizing Alan Watts audio lectures will be included in the game), I've decided to give Mountain a try.Mountain is 2014 game by David ORilley, author of now trending Everything. It's 0.99 € game that allows you to be a randomly generated mountain lost in space. Mountain generation is fueled by player's simple drawings. Once it's generated, Mountain basically allows players two different actions.The first one, the one you'll be enjoying a lot is waiting. Waiting and observing is at the game's core. As time passes, so will seasons, days and night. Soon enough, an idyllic mountain will become home to different random objects such as wall clocks, baseballs, traffic cones and high heel shoes. After some time, your mountain will start looking like a decorated Christmas tree.The other function is experimental piano. By using keyboard, you will be able to play up to 16 tones. Playing speeds up time, but if you play some of the traditional songs such as Marry Had A Little Lamb and Jingle Bells, you will unlock different secrets, and effects of those can be turned on and off.When you really don't get any story, directions and ideas, you tend to pursue your own. That part of human nature has been driving the video game revolution for so long. Telling stories. Experiencing. Feeling. Unfortunately, Mountain's lack of interactive tools doesn't allow you to do anything thought provoking beyond one hour of gameplay. As an experiment, I've seen better ones. As a screensaver, Mountain can suffice. As a philosophical digital experiment, go for Everything.***You have reached the end of a review. However, there's more, plus giveaways, plus cool community of great gamers right athttp://steamcommunity.com/groups/libereviewsFollow the curator's page here:http://store.steampowered.com/curator/10953338/"
