,Recommended,313340,11815344,"Posted: 21 August, 2014",all,murderbits,"There's no reason for debate over whether or not this is a game, so let's get that out of the way, first. A game is a form of play or sport, usually competitive, involving rules that is decided by skill, strength, or luck. Mountain involves none of these things. This should not detract from what it is and not everything developed with tools often used to make games needs to be a game.That aside, here is what you can expect from Mountain:When you launch it, you are asked to draw a few things on the screen with your mouse, to generate a random seed with which your mountain will be generated. After that, you will watch your mountain (a hunk of earth floating in outer space) spin slowly around. Sometimes the weather will change and foliage will change. Sometimes, an item will land on the mountain, like a ball, lollipop, jet engine, ladies shoes, or umbrella. Every so often, the mountain will say something to you, like ""I feel at one with the universe, tonight"".After a bunch of hours, something happens. I don't know what it is, because I fell asleep. When it hit about the 20th hour, it started making a ton of noise and went to a ""game over"" screen.Essentially, Mountain is what used to be considered a demo. A little program that someone would have distributed on a floppy disk for free -- or maybe sold for fifty cents at the local nicotine-filled hacker-computer-shop that we haven't seen much of since the mid 90s. It doesn't really do anything; you don't either. You just look at it until it stops. You can make the screen small and stick it in the corner of your screen, if you like.So, would I recommend it? I wouldn't say it is garbage, by any means. If it seems like something you might be interested in and you buy it with the understanding that there's no game involved and you wont' be doing anything, then it is hard to complain about it costing a dollar -- which is absolutely the right price for this tiny curiosity. Therefore, with those reservations, I'd give this a recommendation."
