76561198039195485,Recommended,313340,13264945,"Posted: 7 December, 2014",all,fabiobollinger,"Should I care for my Mountain? Or should I let it accumulate with trash? Will there be real consequences of what I draw in the openning screen?  Was that baseball there 5 minutes ago? In 'Mountain'There's a persistent sense of ""I wonder if something is about to happen..."" Occasionally it does. In Mountain, you don't play. You expect, you question, you get hopeful, you get disapointed, you get inspired, but most importantly you think. The creator of Mountain specified that this game is best left running for you to occasionally check in on. I left mountain running for 6 hours while I did work. Every so often, I would hear the chyme indicating my Mountain was about to express its pure existential thoughts. What's the point of that thought? Why would a mountain care about the sunrise? Maybe it's not about that, maybe it's a statement. Maybe it's demonstrating the joy of pure life. Maybe not though, maybe it's touching on the cynicisms of life and time?Art is what makes people think. This interactive piece of art will let you poke at it all day and you'll never be satisfied with any conclusions you may create regarding its purpose. You will keep poking, keep wondering. I managed to get a dwarf planet to destroy my mountain - I was killed and the game offered me a 'retry.' Does this imply I failed a goal? What is my goal? Who IS Mountain? I may never find an answer, but I don't think I'll stop asking any time soon.""I don't really know what I am, is that weird?"" Said Mountain just as I typed the last sentence. Don't worry, Mountain, I'm doing my best to find out.If you've ever read the Catcher in the Rye, you know that someone's entire story and entire personality can be revealed through the way they observe the world around them. Not in their actions, necessarily, but the way they think. That's mountain. Don't buy for gameplay, you won't find it. Buy it to experience something new, to think, and to ask questions."
,Recommended,313340,12098397,"Posted: 14 September, 2014",all,BRAINDEAD,"A mountain is a large landform that stretches above the surrounding land in a limited area, usually in the form of a peak. A mountain is generally steeper than a hill. Mountains are formed through tectonic forces or volcanism. These forces can locally raise the surface of the earth. Mountains erode slowly through the action of rivers, weather conditions, and glaciers. A few mountains are isolated summits, but most occur in huge mountain ranges.High elevations on mountains produce colder climates than at sea level. These colder climates strongly affect the ecosystem of mountains: different elevations have different plants and animals. Because of the less hospitable terrain and climate, mountains tend to be used less for agriculture and more for resource extraction and recreation, such as mountain climbing.The highest mountain on Earth is Mount Everest in the Himalayas of Asia, whose summit is 8,849.868 m (29,035 ft) above mean sea level. The highest known mountain on any planet in the Solar System is Olympus Mons on Mars at 21,171 m (69,459 ft)."
