76561198085349542,Recommended,313340,32829498,Posted: 26 June,all,BlueHaven,"Personally, I love this game, if you want to call it that. There's really very little to it:  you just open it, leave it be, and come back to it every once in awhile to see if your mountain has evolved, if anything has changed. It reminds me of those electronic pet games people used to play, except that your mountain doesn't require feeding or anything else from you.My favorite aspect of this game is the ambient sounds. If you zoom in on your mountain you can hear the peaceful weather sounds that come and go, such as rain, wind, thunder, etc. If you zoom out to space, you hear a continuous meditational ""OM"" sound. I often leave this up, just for the audio ambience, to help me relax and unwind while surfing the net or browsing Steam.By the way, you can interact with the mountain to a certain degree. Aside from being able to turn, rotate, and zoom, you can also interact with permanent items that eventually appear. For example, I now have a rake, shovel, and message in a bottle (3 hours in). I can tap on them, or pull them up and reposition them. Funnily enough, when you drop them, they sound like an immense asteroid hitting the earth. Also, I accidently flung the bottle out into deep space, never to return, though a new one eventually appeared (or the old one?).Aside from this, there are random philosophical 'thoughts' that appear occasionally, signaled by a tone. Some of them really make you think about your life.For adjustments, there's a settings menu, with a simple graphics low to high option, as well as the ability to turn sounds off/on, thoughts off/on, windowed/full options, and whether you want auto mode on/off.I only gave 50 cents for this, and consider it well worth it, especially for something so zen-like. Heck, I'd probably give up to $2, maybe even $2.50. I recommend buying it, but just remember it's not really a 'game' as such, so some people may find it a bit boring."
,Recommended,313340,31409629,Posted: 27 April,all,Yossarian,This game is basically SimCity after just one strong hit of peyote.
,Recommended,313340,33259215,Posted: 4 July,all,N E A R H A N,"Before I begin I'm gonna set this straight - this is NOT a game in a traditional sense, rather more like, as someone said before, an intereactive wallpaper. You don't really play it, aside from mashing keys to make songs and occasionally pressing the ""."" key to check in on the mountain. You leave it to run and see how things progress. But for me, at least, its kinda relaxing. Just seeing this mound of earth being drizzled over by whatever that day's weather maybe be it raining frogs or an asteroid shower feels soothing. This, and coupled with the soundtrack, feels good. It's only a buck at normal price, and a great break from all the hectic gameplay of the usual stuff I play. Get it for a neat little distraction that you can occasionally tinker with from time to time."
