,Not Recommended,313340,12199780,"Posted: 23 September, 2014",all,Dinoracha,"While I am all for creative ideas in game design that are often bizarre, experimental or would only be executed by independent developers, Mountain is a clear cut example as to why not all ideas should have a price tag put on them.I have spent almost four hours 'playing' Mountain, though that clocked time was mostly me doing something else while the game ran off to the side. That's because Mountain is an interactive screensaver. Nothing more, nothing less, even if the genres on its Steam store page incorrectly label it as a 'simulation' and 'RPG'. Mountain does attempt to foster actual interaction by allowing you to play musical notes on your keyboard which when a correct sequence is played (Hot Cross Buns, Twinkle Twinkle Little Star, etc), you can cause various effects to rain down on your mountain, like hearts, fireballs or in morbid manner, blood. These effects are only visual, unfortunately, and gameplay in Mountain doesn't improve from there. You can use your mouse to look around your mountain, spin it or zoom in and out for a closer and more distant look, and cleverly enough you can briskly shake your mountain to clear away clouds if you want a clear look at your personal piece of rock (despite the trees and other textures looking incredibly poor). Oh, random space debris will also fly in and crash into your mountain, like a traffic cone, a child's toy block, a futuristic sphere and other oddities that you can then move around or throw away. Why? Video games!Mountain falls apart at the seams once you realize you've exhausted these gameplay elements (and I use that term loosely), since the only progression in the game is the passing of time, the weather and seasons in your little bubble of an atmosphere, since zooming out will reveal your mountain is floating in space for reasons I still can't figure out. Apparently your mountain has emotions and sentience, since every few minutes it will make an observation or statement about the current weather, time of day and how it feels, even if during the night it will claim to be nervous one minute, and then another claim it feels bold from the darkness. Another 'thought' your mountain can have is some kind of existential question or statement regarding its existence, why its out here in space, if the player is a voice inside its head, why is it alone, are there other mountains like it, etc. and so forth (you can also press period to force one of these thoughts if yo﻿u don't want to wait). Apparently this is what has attracted players and journalists to the game, supposedly eliciting emotions and 'feels' from your mountain having a crisis of its own sentience and having to cope and adapt with the bizarre circumstances it finds itself in while 'living' day by day, season by season.﻿The glaring flaw in trying to stir thoughts in the player this way is that Mountain is still a screensaver. Nothing more, nothing less. I've tried to find something positive to say about Mountain, but excluding being able to shake your mountain to clear the clouds being clever, I have nothing. Mountain feels like it's trying to be something unique, but it ends up looking utterly ridiculous and full of itself in the process, and the fact that it carries a price tag doesn't help its case. Yes, ninety-nine cents is a piddly amount which could easily be raised by selling Steam cards, but charging money for screensaver under the guise of an 'ambient procedural mountain game' is an absolute joke, where the punch-line is on the consumer.In no way can I recommend Mountain, even at the price of being a penny shy of a dollar. It is a waste of time, money and patience from the four hours I burned away on this game, trying to make sense of it and realize what the positive talk of it was about.﻿"
,Not Recommended,313340,13261521,"Posted: 6 December, 2014",all,Kris,"This game would be good if you had nothing to do or just needed something to help calm you down - but i would not recommend it, as it can get quite boring after half a hour of waiting and nothing happening."
