,Recommended,313340,11771106,"Posted: 18 August, 2014",all,Zephri,"All my life I was plagued by an unsettling awareness that something was missing. I was incomplete, a person born into the wrong body and unable to come to terms with myself as a human being. Who am I? What am I doing with my life? What is all this even for? These questions gnawed at me, eating me away from the inside until I was hollow and thinking I couldn't live with myself anymore.Then I played Mountain.I realized what was missing from my life, there was a cavernous hole in my psyche in the shape of a mountain. A chunk of myself spinning in the void, disconnected and fragmented, completely without purpose. I watched as it slowly rotated, each angle subtly different, like a babe beneath a jingling plush mobile I was mesmerized.What am I doing? I pondered as a placidly watched the seasons pass me by, weathering me down, making me smoother, gentler, capable only of idly commenting on the notion of time and how something so indifferent to my existence can affect me so greatly. Has this face changed since the last time I gazed upon it? Its creases and angles seemed inherently familiar, yet the pattern of life across its surface strangely foreign each time I see it anew. I was always getting older, spinning in place as life moved on around me, embedding me with memories of a life once lived, leaving me with impressions, pieces of the world around me, seemingly random and yet unshakable.Where am I? Lost in an endless and empty vacuum, suspended in a spherical prison pieced together from the materials of living matter I've sorted and categorized to be able to comprehend as existence. Unable to see beyond it to greater meaning. Unable to feel the difference between moving through space and space moving through me. I cannot fathom a reason for my being, why I ended up one place and not another, if I am alone through action or if I am made alone in my awareness of self.Who am I? I knew there was more beneath the surface, if only I could dig my nails into that crust, pull at its crumbling edges and explore what skeletal frame held up this facade, knowing... Nay, praying, that there was something more to me than this ponderous slope of earthen matter. Something to express in more than a few staggered notes, something greater than the deafening silence. But no matter what I grasped at, what extrusion I prodded or angle I explored, I was faced with nothing but the naked truth of myself:I am Mountain.TL;DR 6/10 - Most hipster screensaver ever."
