,Recommended,313340,11803631,"Posted: 21 August, 2014",all,{[SAC]} Elihu Aran,"It's always the same.A few questions are asked; sure, they're fairly different every time, but what's relevant is that they're always questions.The first time? You don't know what to do until it says draw something.Connections are made. You realize it's making you draw an abstract concept.Does it do anything? Who knows. Maybe it's a metaphor.Then it draws you a mountain.It draws you.You do what anybody else would do. You click on it. It stops. You drag it left. It spins faster to the left. You drag it right. It spins to the right. You scroll for fun. The camera zooms in and out accordingly.Suddnely, a sound. A wonky chord, played upon a piano.The mountain says something. Was it you? Did you do anything? The answer is no. You didn't do anything. The mountain has thoughts. It thinks.Later, a few presses of your keyboard reveal that certain keys produce musical notes, and that there's even one to make the mountain speak, to think. This isn't the natural way of things. The mountain thinks, speaks on it's own terms. It feels forced otherwise.After playing around with the notes for a bit, you feel adventerous. What happens if you play these notes? What happens if that song plays? What happens, if for no reason at all, you decide to play that five note tune fromClose Encounters?Maybe it's best you don't right this instant. A time for everything, and such.Then a loud noise, and a shake of the camera. What happened? What is it?You search the mountain for any clues. Then you see it.A giant rubber duck.It's right there, buried face-first in the side of your mountain. You can't see it from the front to confirm it's a rubber duck, but there's nothing else that's quite got that shape.So you click on it. Maybe there's a rubber duck noise. Maybe not. Nothing much happens. So you click it and hold it.It shakes. It pops out of the mountain. In shock, you let go of the mouse. It flies back into the mountain. It makes you chuckle.The mountain keeps thinking, keeps spinning, just doing it's thing.Then you remember theClose Encounterssong-tune-thing. You plunk out the keys badly enough to figure it out, then prepare to play the thing for real.The final note rings out. A giant red eye appears out from nowhere and comes ever closer to your mountain. The tense music begins, growing ever louder as the eye gets ever closer.And then it reaches the mountain. The eye destroys your mountain. The thing that ou didn't work at all for.And you feel a loss.And then you start again."
,Recommended,313340,11803858,"Posted: 21 August, 2014",all,Echo Nine,"Alright look. I don't see this as a game but a simulation or a piece of iteractive software (like how some people have characters that live on their desktop).I'm going to point out why I like Mountain.Firstly - With sound blocking headphones on the ambience of the game is amazing and you can choose to have the sound play while minimized.Secondly - The world around your mountain is influenced by what you do. The more and faster you play the piano the faster the mountain spins causing the days to go by quicker. Spinning the camera causes the wind to remove the clouds and interact with raining objects.Thirdly - There are a lot of hidden things in this 'game' to find with your piano keyboard.Forth - It's only 1 dollar... I enjoy having it open while I am working on things.TLDR:The shaders seem to glitch every now and then which is a downside but a part from that I find it interesting for a dollar. If you are expecting this game to something that will blow your mind or be marked on gaming history as the next thing it wont, and why should it?. It's a nice zen 'game' to have open while you work."
,Recommended,313340,11803879,"Posted: 21 August, 2014",all,Elfilon,"It's not tehcnically a game but it is super relaxing. Nice bit of ambient noise, the odd thought from the mountain. Don't buy it if you want a huge amount of interaction but I rather enjoy watching it."
,Recommended,313340,11803665,"Posted: 21 August, 2014",all,Xariann,"As a game I should really downvote this. But there are enough reviews here to show that this isn't really a game, so since we already established that, I am going to review this for what it is, an intriguing piece of art. I am an art lover, and as such I find this interesting.The concept of a lonely mountain that goes through changes, comments on its existance, has reactions and so on is just a really good concept. It lives up to the creators of Her.You kind of wonder if this mountain at some point is going to become so evolved that it will go away to a ""higher place"" with the other Mountains. And you know that this isn't going to happen, that obviously this isn't as complex as the ficticious AI OS starring in Her. But your mind goes places, and then your attention is brought back to the Mountain, even as I type this, as the sound of dawn chimes.You are there going about your business, doing your own thing, and so is Mountain. So why blame Mountain for living its own life? Yet unsuspecting that you can turn it off at any time, only to resume from where it left off the next time you turn it on.But you could ask, are we also all unaware of some higher power that is watching us from a computer screen while we go about our lives?You'll probably say, ""You are crazy, of course we are not.""Yet all I have been trying to do here is to embrace and show what kind of concept Mountain really is. At least my artistic interpretation. Look elsewhere if you want a game, but if you want a piece of art, a silent ""companion"" then you might want to spend the little money it costs. If not, nobody forces you to buy this, you keep going about your business and play the games you enjoy, just as Mountain goes about its own.P.S.: If you really don't like your Mountain, you can always ""as,zb"""
,Recommended,313340,11804441,"Posted: 21 August, 2014",all,Mae,"I haven't been playing this for very long now, i know.First I just started, was seeing the mountain, and thought ""wow, so it really isn't much"". Few controls, a spinning mountain.Then I started reading the reviews and thought ""maybe I should do the same as these people"" and started naming a rock Sam. After some minutes I already forgot which rock was Sam.But after ~15 to 20 minutes a group of three fir trees came to my eye and I came to like them. They grew on a kind of bare side of the mountain and I don't know why, but I was happy they were a group of three so that no one of them was alone. By now there are more trees, and I'm slowly entering the autumn season.A table crashed into the top of my mountain. I can only see two legs of it. I don't care about him, since he left my group of trees in peace.The mountain just asked ""where do I come from?"" and my first thought was ""sorry, that's my fault""."
